                accompanies the vertuous, doeth not worke more mischiefe for the finall ouerthrow of a noble and deseruing man, thē Flattery doth,

for driuing that noble and deseruing man into the snares of enuie. No man can be, or should be reputed a God; and then how easie it is for any man of the choycest temper, of the soundest apprehension, of the gracefullest education, of the sincerest austeritie of life; how easie it is for him to fall into many errours, into many vnbecomming follies, into many passions, and affections: his onely being a man is both sufficient proofe, and yet sufficient excuse.

The eloquentest and grauest Diuine of all the Ancients,
                  Augustine.
